<p>
    This entire unit has considered inverse square laws.
    But it begs the question, how did the original scientists (Newton and Coulomb)
    discover these formulas?
    It is intuitive that the force of gravitation should be directly proportional
    to the mass, but why is it inversely proportional to distance squared?
    In fact, Newton had an intuition that the inverse square law was the correct relationship.
    Based on this intuition, he calculated what results would follow.
    But why did he have that intuition in the first place?
</p>

<p>
    Isaac Newton had spent much of his youth experimenting and studying light.
    It is possible he thought of his inverse square law by examining light.
    We will draw a comparison.
</p>

