<h4>
    Connection to Gravitation
</h4>


<p>
    What does this analysis have to do with gravity?
    Just like the intensity of light, the magnitude of gravitational force
    is inversely proportional to the square of the distance from the source of that gravity,
    according to the formula
    $$
    F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2}.
    $$
    Imagine that one of the masses is the source of gravity and the other is receiving the gravity.
    For example, think of the sun as the source of gravity and all its planets as receivers.
    You can even think of gravitational waves traveling from one thing to another which are similar to the photons,
    although truly understanding gravitational waves is a far more advanced topic.
    Just like the energy of the light bulb spreads out as you were farther from the bulb, the force from the sun spreads out,
    so that Mercury gets stronger gravity than Venus, which receives stronger gravity than earth, which receives stronger
    gravity than Mars.
    [Of course, we know from Newton's Third Law that this give-receiver relationship goes both ways,
    each planet exerts and equal magnitude of gravitational force on the sun. Here, the analogy with the light breaks down.]
</p>

